A PPF diagram shows that if a developing country prioritises consumption, lack of investment means the PPF moves inwards. If growth is prioritised, the PPF moves outwards. Eventually citizens can move out of absolute poverty. However, if gains are not equally shared, living standards overall will not increase. India and China have experienced rapid growth but significant numbers remain in poverty due to inequality. For poorer countries, prioritising economic growth seems necessary but not sufficient.

"GDP growth on its own does not mean a better life for everyone particularly in countries that are already wealthy." The HDI includes years of schooling and life expectancy. Costa Rica has GDP per capita of ~$14,000 vs $52,000 for the US, but higher life expectancy. On the Happy Planet Index, Costa Rica tops the table. Relative poverty (influenced by inequality) has a significant impact on social exclusion.

Development rather than growth may be more important – reducing conflict, improving financial systems, property rights and intergenerational mobility. For the very poorest countries, growth is essential. For others, it is how growth is achieved and how resources are used. Achieving economic growth needs some priority, but whether it is highest depends on circumstances.

