### 25 Marker: Income Tax vs Austerity for Budget Deficit (Q8)

**Question:** Evaluate whether a significant increase in UK income tax rates would be a better way of reducing the budget deficit than austerity. (25 marks)

**Point 1 – Austerity has been damaging:** Government spending is necessary for public goods, correcting market failures, and merit goods (education, healthcare). Cuts have been damaging. But higher tax rates adversely affect incentives to work, innovate and be entrepreneurial. Higher rates reduce UK attractiveness for FDI. The Laffer curve supports the idea that revenues can fall beyond a certain tax rate. Free market economists say higher rates are damaging; Keynesians agree – higher taxes reduce AD, so negative output gap persists longer. Significant income tax increases do not seem better.

**Point 2 – Deficits may not be harmful:** A Keynesian would argue the deficit provides a net injection into the circular flow, helping close negative output gaps via the multiplier. Financial crowding out (bonds needing higher rates) is the only risk – but UK gilts remain a safer investment with low yields. Free market economists argue resource crowding out is damaging as the economy tends quickly to full employment.

**Point 3 – Fairness:** The UK has unequal income/wealth distribution. But higher rate taxpayers can avoid taxes. Increasing rates that higher earners avoid but lower earners don't would do little for equity.

**Conclusion:** Disincentive effects, avoidance risk, and FDI impact all argue against. The case for significant increases is not strong.

