### 15 Marker: Why Currency Value Falls (Q9, 2019 Section B)

**Question:** Explain why the value of a currency may fall in a floating exchange rate system. (15 marks)

An exchange rate is the price of one currency in terms of another. A floating exchange rate is determined solely by market forces.

**Point 1 – Current account deficit:** If imports exceed exports, supply of pounds rises (to obtain foreign currency for imports). Excess supply at the original rate drives the exchange rate down (e.g. £1=$1.50 to £1=$1.20).

**Point 2 – FDI outflows:** If UK companies make FDI abroad, they supply pounds to obtain foreign currency. Firms might relocate to avoid tariffs and border delays, especially with complex cross-border supply chains.

**Point 3 – Interest rate differentials:** If interest rates are higher elsewhere, hot money flows out. Pounds are supplied into forex markets, and the value falls. This may happen because of differing inflationary prospects.

