### 15 Marker: Monetary Transmission Mechanism (Q11, 2019 Paper)

**Question:** Explain how changes in interest rates affect inflation. (15 marks)

The monetary transmission mechanism is the means by which interest rate changes affect AD and ultimately inflationary pressure. Bank Rate acts as an anchor for rates throughout the economy.

**Point 1 – Consumption and investment:** Higher Bank Rate increases the incentive to save (higher opportunity cost of consumption). Borrowing-financed consumption falls. Higher rates reduce asset prices (bonds, property), reducing wealth and consumption. For firms, investment falls as borrowing is more expensive and future consumption expectations are lower. Domestic demand falls.

**Point 2 – Exchange rate channel:** Higher rates cause the pound to appreciate (hot money inflows). If Marshall Lerner conditions hold, the current account worsens, reducing external demand. Overall AD falls.

**Point 3 – Effect on inflation:** Firms hold excess supplies at the original price level. They cut prices and output. Multiplier effects lead to further falls in AD. Price level falls from P to P1. Lower import costs reduce cost-push pressures and CPI directly for imported finished goods in the basket.

