## Paper 3 (Synoptic)

Paper 3 is a synoptic paper containing both macro and micro. It starts with 30 MCQs, 4 extracts with data. There is a 15 marker and 25 marker (same structures as above), plus a 10 marker.

### 10 Marker Structure
- Make 3 points in relation to the statement
- Each point should contain: an argument, data to back it up, analysis/chains of reasoning, limitations of the data, judgement

### 10 Mark Scheme
A good response that:
- is well organised with at least three relevant, well-developed issues
- makes effective use of numerical/statistical data
- shows appreciation of limitations of the data
- includes a supported final judgement

### 10 Marker Model Answer: Housing Affordability

**Question:** To what extent do the data suggest houses in the UK were more affordable in 2017 than in 2007?

"Most owner occupiers finance the purchase of their house by borrowing, using a mortgage." Figure 3 shows the house price to earnings ratio for first time buyers fell from 5.4:1 (Q4 2007) to 5.2:1 (Q4 2017). This suggests affordability improved. However, post-financial crisis lenders require bigger deposits, likely offsetting this small difference. "Today the median price of a house is almost eight times median earnings, an all-time record" (2017), suggesting less affordability than 2007.

Mortgage interest rates fell from ~7.5% (Dec 2007) to ~4.25% (Dec 2017), suggesting improved affordability. Mortgage payments as % of mean take home pay improved from 51% to 32%. But it would be useful to have dispersion data and other essential expenditure costs. This only shows those who could make a purchase.

Average house prices rose 19.85% and weekly earnings 20.47% from 2007-2017, suggesting broadly unchanged affordability. But these are nominal figures. Adjusting for inflation, real earnings were very little changed. Disaggregated data would likely show significant regional differences.

Only to a limited extent can we conclude houses were more affordable in 2017. The balance of evidence suggests the opposite, especially for certain groups.

